how they related to Hearthstone and sort of the ideas behind them.

13
00:00:57,854 --> 00:01:04,437
So, the first thing that worked out very, very, very well for Hearthstone is that we

14
00:01:04,477 --> 00:01:06,258
were able to iterate fast.

15
00:01:06,919 --> 00:01:10,981
And that's certainly something that you will hear over and over if you go to GDC talks,

16
00:01:11,061 --> 00:01:14,602
it's not like rocket science or anything to iterate fast.

17
00:01:15,243 --> 00:01:17,844
And certainly on Hearthstone we found that...

18
00:01:18,544 --> 00:01:23,365
we had tons and tons of bad ideas that we needed to try and then not do and so

19
00:01:23,385 --> 00:01:28,146
that quick iteration let us not do all of those ideas and I guess the

20
00:01:28,166 --> 00:01:35,187
interesting thing is is perhaps how we did the quick iteration so to start we

21
00:01:35,247 --> 00:01:40,008
had a lot of pure design time and what I mean by that is me and Ben Brode the

22
00:01:40,148 --> 00:01:44,389
other designer on the project spent a lot of time before anything else really

23
00:01:44,449 --> 00:01:47,130
happened trying to figure out what the design of the game was

24
00:01:48,324 --> 00:01:55,750
And I would love to say that that was planned, but accurately what I can say is that instead

25
00:01:55,770 --> 00:02:00,614
all of our engineers were moved to another project for a while to help out with that project.

26
00:02:02,275 --> 00:02:05,277
And so we got a lot of inadvertent pure design time.

27
00:02:06,118 --> 00:02:09,141
And for us, it was very, very important

28
00:02:09,161 --> 00:02:10,102
for a couple of reasons.

29
00:02:11,023 --> 00:02:12,925
The first reason why this design time was important

30
00:02:12,945 --> 00:02:14,646
was of course because our engineers

31
00:02:14,987 --> 00:02:16,388
were not asking us questions

32
00:02:16,528 --> 00:02:18,049
and bothering us asking those questions

33
00:02:18,089 --> 00:02:19,291
so we could focus on design.

34
00:02:21,247 --> 00:02:27,170
Actually one of the big reasons it was important is because if we had had engineers to ask us those questions

35
00:02:27,731 --> 00:02:31,973
We would have answered their questions, and we wouldn't have had enough information

36
00:02:32,884 --> 00:02:36,265
to actually know what we were going to do in the final design.

37
00:02:36,645 --> 00:02:40,626
And so we would have told them things that later on would have kind of hosed us

38
00:02:41,186 --> 00:02:44,667
because we would have later on said okay here's our design now and they would

39
00:02:44,687 --> 00:02:47,128
have gone you know a year ago when you told us

40
00:02:47,208 --> 00:02:50,569
that you wanted it to work like this well we implemented like this and then

41
00:02:50,589 --> 00:02:54,490
it would have made it much more difficult or impossible to do the actual

42
00:02:54,550 --> 00:02:57,051
design that we sort of wanted to to follow through with.

43
00:02:58,304 --> 00:03:05,648
And in this pure design time, since of course we had a couple of designers and we had our lead artist as well, but no engineers,

44
00:03:07,289 --> 00:03:10,190
we spent a lot of that time doing paper design.

45
00:03:10,850 --> 00:03:20,315
And it works of course very well for our game because our game is based and comes from the physical collectible card game genre, that's its basis.

46
00:03:20,335 --> 00:03:22,976
But I actually think that there's a lot of games that could end up doing...

47
00:03:24,358 --> 00:03:26,740
more paper design time than they otherwise do.

48
00:03:27,541 --> 00:03:30,444
And certainly I can say, as far as game development goes,

49
00:03:30,604 --> 00:03:33,887
one reason that it was super useful for us to do this is because,

50
00:03:34,568 --> 00:03:36,270
strictly from an expense point of view, I mean,

51
00:03:36,811 --> 00:03:38,452
having two designers working on stuff,

52
00:03:38,572 --> 00:03:43,017
doing paper design is a cheaper thing to do than having a full team rolling.

53
00:03:44,257 --> 00:03:47,199
I can talk a little bit about this specific design.

54
00:03:47,219 --> 00:03:51,781
So when we were working on the game, we were trying to solve a whole bunch of different

55
00:03:51,841 --> 00:03:52,721
design problems.

56
00:03:53,341 --> 00:03:58,524
And this specific card or idea was trying to solve the problem of the heroes feeling

57
00:03:58,604 --> 00:03:59,464
really powerful.

58
00:04:00,024 --> 00:04:03,446
Because when we were working on Hearthstone, one of the ideas we had is we wanted heroes

59
00:04:03,826 --> 00:04:08,748
to not just be a punching bag, but to be this powerful character that actually interacts

60
00:04:09,148 --> 00:04:13,470
with the environment and isn't just something that gets beat up.

61
00:04:14,299 --> 00:04:21,905
And the issue we had with that, or sort of the reason we went in this direction is we decided,

62
00:04:21,945 --> 00:04:26,569
hey, maybe we can make a really powerful hero who doesn't show up until later in the game.

63
00:04:26,609 --> 00:04:30,272
So there's a fortress that you have to smash your way through before the hero leaps out.

64
00:04:30,852 --> 00:04:33,394
And then once the hero leaps out, he can actually be powerful,

65
00:04:33,455 --> 00:04:38,498
and we actually had a whole system where you spent points buying super cool weapons and armor and stuff for him.

66
00:04:39,639 --> 00:04:44,582
But there ended up being a number of problems with this model not the least of which being that you

67
00:04:44,782 --> 00:04:47,944
Generally didn't destroy the enemy's fortress you just built up a huge army

68
00:04:48,424 --> 00:04:52,307
Waited till you had overwhelming force and then crushed their fortress and hero at the same time

69
00:04:53,227 --> 00:04:56,589
But it was very very valuable for us to try things like this discover

70
00:04:56,609 --> 00:04:59,811
They were terrible and and move on just in a paper format

71
00:05:01,340 --> 00:05:05,567
Another thing that worked out very very well for us is we made a flash prototype of the game.

72
00:05:05,747 --> 00:05:11,175
This is a picture of the game sort of in the middle of our flash prototype ideas,

73
00:05:11,235 --> 00:05:13,258
not very early, but not towards the end.

74
00:05:15,295 --> 00:05:20,537
What worked out well for this is that we got to try a whole bunch of the ideas in the Flash prototype,

75
00:05:20,597 --> 00:05:26,900
and our final Flash prototype mechanically actually looks almost identical to how the

76
00:05:27,620 --> 00:05:33,082
game looks today as far as mechanics. I mean it doesn't have the pretty 3D world and a lot of

77
00:05:33,102 --> 00:05:37,223
the cool effects and all that kind of stuff, and some of the cards are certainly changed,

78
00:05:38,204 --> 00:05:43,265
but the game field itself and the basic interactions and mechanics and UI were all

79
00:05:43,866 --> 00:05:44,586
ready and done.

80
00:05:45,600 --> 00:05:50,081
And what that meant was when we finished with this Flash prototype and we were ready to start building the real game,

81
00:05:50,121 --> 00:05:52,882
we pointed to the Flash prototype and told our engineers,

82
00:05:53,563 --> 00:05:57,644
hey, we're just going to sit around for a few months, why don't you just make that thing that's this game right here?

83
00:05:58,524 --> 00:06:07,207
And it let the engineers make the back end of the game exactly how it was going to end up being design-wise,

84
00:06:07,227 --> 00:06:11,529
so we didn't have to later on make changes and get in trouble because there were engineering problems behind the scenes.

85
00:06:11,569 --> 00:06:14,970
So it was a huge advantage for us to build this Flash prototype.

86
00:06:15,530 --> 00:06:20,553
And of course it also meant that we got to very quickly try a whole bunch of ideas, put

87
00:06:20,573 --> 00:06:24,094
them into the Flash prototype, not worry that it was junking up the code because we knew

88
00:06:24,134 --> 00:06:26,155
we were going to throw it away in the long run.

89
00:06:28,516 --> 00:06:34,419
So another very important thing for us in Hearthstone was sharing the vision with our

90
00:06:34,439 --> 00:06:34,759
team.

91
00:06:36,440 --> 00:06:41,122
Certainly everybody on our team is going to be participating in making the game.

92
00:06:42,682 --> 00:06:48,928
If you've ever been on a game where everybody on the team is not making the same game, it doesn't go so well.

93
00:06:49,449 --> 00:06:53,572
And yeah, there's a lot of ways of communicating what the game is all about.

94
00:06:53,812 --> 00:06:59,137
You can communicate it via, you know, just talking a lot about it or showing some example games

95
00:06:59,457 --> 00:07:03,081
or sharing design documents which normally make people fall asleep.

96
00:07:04,342 --> 00:07:10,709
But what we did is we had a set of six stakes in the ground and these were the

97
00:07:10,769 --> 00:07:16,496
basic ideas that we used to communicate both to ourselves and and to new people

98
00:07:16,536 --> 00:07:19,459
who are joining the team and pretty much all of the people who are involved in

99
00:07:19,499 --> 00:07:22,062
around the game what the game was all about.

100
00:07:22,762 --> 00:07:26,624
And so that at a high level made sure that everybody who was making the game

101
00:07:26,844 --> 00:07:29,986
was making the same game and had these same high-level ideas.

102
00:07:30,446 --> 00:07:34,007
Yeah, these are actually two of the the six stakes in the ground and I'll

103
00:07:34,027 --> 00:07:38,770
certainly be talking about some more of them later, but these stakes were just

104
00:07:38,830 --> 00:07:41,711
critical for communicating to the rest of the team what the game was.

105
00:07:42,688 --> 00:07:47,153
and the reason why that ended up being so important, or I think it's important really in all games,

106
00:07:47,593 --> 00:07:52,239
is that certainly on the Hearthstone team, everybody on the team is a designer,

107
00:07:52,419 --> 00:07:55,442
and I think this is really just true across all of game development,

108
00:07:56,003 --> 00:07:59,827
that all of your engineers and artists and pretty much everybody involved in the game

109
00:07:59,887 --> 00:08:01,949
is making design decisions, large and small.

110
00:08:02,850 --> 00:08:23,118
and there's a couple of ways you can go about sort of designing the game and the way we decided to go about it is that on the design side we sort of said here's the big way we want this idea to work, here's sort of the big picture idea behind whatever the system is that our engineers or artists or whatever we're putting in and then the engineer or artist has

111
00:08:24,178 --> 00:08:27,859
both the knowledge because they understand sort of the the big vision and

112
00:08:27,879 --> 00:08:29,220
also the the

113
00:08:30,420 --> 00:08:34,802
on the ground knowledge to make the right implementation choices there because

114
00:08:34,822 --> 00:08:39,644
There's often going to be a lot of small details that the person who's actually doing the implementation

115
00:08:39,704 --> 00:08:43,946
You know the engineer artist or whatnot is going to notice that's going to be hard to notice up front

116
00:08:45,357 --> 00:08:46,937
You, of course, could handle this as a designer

117
00:08:46,977 --> 00:08:50,178
by putting out a design document that

118
00:08:50,258 --> 00:08:51,599
details every little detail.

119
00:08:51,639 --> 00:08:54,280
But I've had bad experience with that in the past,

120
00:08:54,340 --> 00:08:57,701
because design documents end up being outdated about two

121
00:08:57,781 --> 00:08:59,742
seconds, usually, after you send them out.

122
00:09:00,502 --> 00:09:03,063
And you can't really cover all the details.

123
00:09:03,523 --> 00:09:06,144
So sort of along the lines of this,

124
00:09:06,224 --> 00:09:07,845
one of the things that was very important for us,

125
00:09:07,905 --> 00:09:10,386
and I certainly recommend, is making sure

126
00:09:10,446 --> 00:09:13,187
that everybody on your team has what

127
00:09:13,247 --> 00:09:14,547
I think of as designer brain.

128
00:09:15,567 --> 00:09:18,128
and when looking at somebody to be on our team,

129
00:09:18,248 --> 00:09:20,648
I'm much more excited about an engineer

130
00:09:20,728 --> 00:09:24,069
who is a good engineer, who has designer brain

131
00:09:24,329 --> 00:09:25,870
and sort of can think like a designer

132
00:09:25,910 --> 00:09:27,190
as an engaged in the game,

133
00:09:27,510 --> 00:09:29,190
rather than an amazing engineer

134
00:09:29,711 --> 00:09:32,131
who's not really into the game you're making,

135
00:09:32,191 --> 00:09:34,332
they're not really interested in playing it,

136
00:09:34,412 --> 00:09:36,812
they're not really, don't have strong designer brain.

137
00:09:36,852 --> 00:09:39,213
So it made a world of difference for us on Hearthstone

138
00:09:39,253 --> 00:09:40,933
that sort of everybody on the team

139
00:09:41,413 --> 00:09:42,994
was able to make those design decisions

140
00:09:43,054 --> 00:09:44,954
and let us move forward together sort of as a whole.

141
00:09:47,895 --> 00:09:54,538
So, simplifying Hearthstone is probably at a high level our biggest goal from the very

142
00:09:54,578 --> 00:09:54,918
beginning.

143
00:09:54,958 --> 00:10:00,481
I mean our thought about Hearthstone as a whole was we wanted to make a game that took

144
00:10:00,521 --> 00:10:04,462
what's cool about collectible card games and made them accessible to a lot more people.

145
00:10:05,923 --> 00:10:11,706
Collectible card games in general are pretty complicated beasts that are pretty intimidating to get into

146
00:10:12,067 --> 00:10:18,030
and so we wanted to make sure that we made a game that everybody could sort of understand and start playing immediately.

147
00:10:19,709 --> 00:10:30,293
And one of the things that that meant was we started questioning the basics of what it meant to make a collectible card game or for something to be a collectible card game.

148
00:10:30,693 --> 00:10:42,157
So for instance, there's a lot of collectible card games that have a lot of specific different turns and you have to understand this phase and this phase and this phase and what can be done in each of those phases.

149
00:10:42,738 --> 00:10:44,778
And we decided, okay, we're going to rip all of that out.

150
00:10:45,239 --> 00:10:50,069
The only phase, there's only one phase, the time you get to do stuff, your turn.

151
00:10:50,570 --> 00:10:55,180
And during that turn you actually can just do whatever the heck you want to do in any order.

152
00:10:57,114 --> 00:11:01,477
One of the reasons ways that turned out very well is because it actually adds some tactical depth

153
00:11:01,857 --> 00:11:08,761
and one of our general rules when we're looking at simplifying a system is can we simplify that

154
00:11:08,801 --> 00:11:15,766
system without removing sort of depth of play and in fact in this case as we removed sort of

155
00:11:15,786 --> 00:11:17,907
the turn order in a lot of ways it added depth of play.

156
00:11:19,671 --> 00:11:24,974
Another basic thing that we sort of thought about and challenged when working on Hearthstone

157
00:11:25,695 --> 00:11:32,399
was the traditional collectible card game resource model, which traditionally has your

158
00:11:32,459 --> 00:11:36,882
resources being cards that are drawn, that are part of your collection, just like your

159
00:11:37,142 --> 00:11:39,443
creatures and spells and that you build your deck out of them.

160
00:11:41,568 --> 00:11:48,312
for a whole bunch of different reasons we felt like it was pretty important for us to simplify the game in that area and to make it so that the

161
00:11:48,952 --> 00:11:56,897
resources were in fact a thing that you got automatically every turn rather than a thing that was a card in your hand

162
00:11:57,357 --> 00:11:59,338
and there's a bunch of different reasons for this

163
00:12:00,318 --> 00:12:03,660
certainly one of them is as a new player of a collectible card game

164
00:12:04,000 --> 00:12:08,603
and I actually can even say for myself who is a very experienced player of collectible card games

165
00:12:08,923 --> 00:12:10,924
whenever I look at a collectible card game and go what

166
00:12:11,615 --> 00:12:17,677
percentage of mana or resources or whatever I should put in the deck I generally go online

167
00:12:17,697 --> 00:12:22,078
and look up something because it's just very complicated to figure out how you should build

168
00:12:22,138 --> 00:12:22,458
a deck.

169
00:12:23,618 --> 00:12:30,000
And also putting resources in your deck is not nearly as exciting as minions and spells

170
00:12:30,040 --> 00:12:33,601
so if I'm putting together an awesome deck I want to go, I'm going to put fireballs and

171
00:12:33,641 --> 00:12:34,941
giants and dragons and...

172
00:12:35,868 --> 00:12:41,573
resources is just it was not as exciting. And lastly it actually helped speed play

173
00:12:42,194 --> 00:12:47,139
which was really important to us for Hearthstone to make sure that the game played pretty fast

174
00:12:47,819 --> 00:12:51,803
and normally in a collectible card game I have two choices at the start of my turn I go

175
00:12:51,823 --> 00:12:55,887
am I going to play a resource or which resource am I going to play and then I choose to do the

176
00:12:55,927 --> 00:13:00,191
cool thing which is playing my spell playing my minion you know that sort of thing and so

177
00:13:00,351 --> 00:13:01,532
this speeded that up as well.

178
00:13:04,711 --> 00:13:09,715
Another thing, this is sort of a geeky thing that makes me happy, but it's also a good example as well,

179
00:13:09,776 --> 00:13:15,301
is that we were able to effectively remove the idea of exhaustion in a lot of ways.

180
00:13:16,302 --> 00:13:24,430
And to me, why this is cool is as we were simplifying the game, we made a lot of specific smaller choices to simplify things

181
00:13:24,790 --> 00:13:28,894
that let us do something on a larger scale that felt simpler.

182
00:13:29,454 --> 00:13:34,279
And the smaller things that we did as we were working on Hearthstone is when we were working on the game,

183
00:13:34,880 --> 00:13:39,884
we were talking about, well, do we want minions in play to be able to have an ability that you can activate?

184
00:13:39,904 --> 00:13:46,110
You know, a lot of collectible card games let you use either attack with your minion or use it to do something else.

185
00:13:47,632 --> 00:13:49,354
From a UI point of view we looked at it

186
00:13:49,374 --> 00:13:53,678
And we went we really like it that I can single click on a minion

187
00:13:54,099 --> 00:13:58,723
And it's always going to mean attack. We don't have to have a pop-up menu. We don't have to have left click right click

188
00:13:58,943 --> 00:14:03,788
It's it's a very simple thing so we decided for you know the the shipping of Hearthstone

189
00:14:04,129 --> 00:14:10,375
We're not going to have any abilities on on minions that are triggered by you activating them. You just attack with your minions

190
00:14:12,641 --> 00:14:18,964
Then a separate thing that we did was as we were looking at defenses and how creatures defend themselves.

191
00:14:19,745 --> 00:14:30,070
Traditionally, if I have a guy who can stop enemy attackers, you would, you know, tap or exhaust or whatever the term is depending on the game to block an enemy attacker.

192
00:14:30,770 --> 00:14:34,092
and we, at first we were thinking that was the right way to go

193
00:14:34,772 --> 00:14:38,273
we didn't really like the fact that it was a response on the enemy's turn

194
00:14:38,674 --> 00:14:42,275
and then I think it was actually, it was a long time ago, but I think it was actually a bug

195
00:14:42,895 --> 00:14:46,617
where the taunt actually stayed up permanently

196
00:14:47,357 --> 00:14:50,458
and we played it for a little bit like that and we liked it

197
00:14:50,478 --> 00:14:54,460
and we thought, hey this is great, let's get rid of a defensive creature having to

198
00:14:54,520 --> 00:14:55,680
you know, taunt or exhaust or...

199
00:14:56,360 --> 00:14:59,782
tap or exhaust or whatever to stop an attacker and

200
00:15:00,263 --> 00:15:03,184
Once we got rid of those two things we realized that

201
00:15:04,044 --> 00:15:07,706
This concept of tapping or exhaustion normally applies to a bunch of different things

202
00:15:07,766 --> 00:15:12,609
But for us at this point all it really applies to is whether the creature has attacked or not

203
00:15:13,249 --> 00:15:16,652
So what that meant was when we were doing our tutorial, we could say,

204
00:15:16,732 --> 00:15:19,554
hey, if the creature can attack, it has a green glow around it.

205
00:15:19,654 --> 00:15:20,655
If it can't, it doesn't.

206
00:15:21,135 --> 00:15:22,536
We're not explaining anything more to you.

207
00:15:22,576 --> 00:15:24,498
In fact, we only barely explain that.

208
00:15:24,958 --> 00:15:28,061
And so this whole concept sort of goes away,

209
00:15:29,121 --> 00:15:32,324
and you can understand the game much more quickly early on.

210
00:15:35,194 --> 00:15:38,937
Summoning Sickness is something that is also traditionally in collectible card games,

211
00:15:39,097 --> 00:15:43,501
and it's a mechanic where a creature, when it first comes into play, cannot attack that turn.

212
00:15:44,535 --> 00:15:51,498
And we didn't like this very much either because it had the complexity of a creature could either not be able to attack because it already attacked,

213
00:15:51,958 --> 00:15:55,319
or a creature could not be able to attack because it had just come into play.

214
00:15:56,140 --> 00:16:03,102
And so, and I don't again remember if this was when we were doing the flash prototype or doing it with physical cards,

215
00:16:03,182 --> 00:16:10,525
but we decided, hey, let's try to remove this and see what happens, and we removed it, and it was really, really bad.

