00:26:05,322 --> 00:26:10,945
So this is a point that has a lot more to do probably with our games than a lot of games you're working on,

348
00:26:11,085 --> 00:26:12,826
and that is embracing the medium.

349
00:26:13,287 --> 00:26:18,090
And to us what that means is we're coming from this physical CCG space,

350
00:26:18,570 --> 00:26:20,131
and we're going to a digital space.

351
00:26:20,811 --> 00:26:24,414
And our goal was to make the best digital collectible card game we could,

352
00:26:24,454 --> 00:26:25,614
so we didn't want to end up...

353
00:26:26,475 --> 00:26:29,516
thinking about or getting stuck with any of the things that work great in a

354
00:26:29,576 --> 00:26:35,978
physical space and do not work as well in a digital space and there were a

355
00:26:35,998 --> 00:26:39,660
number of those. Probably the biggest thing that we implemented along those

356
00:26:39,700 --> 00:26:40,620
lines were secrets.

357
00:26:41,541 --> 00:26:57,038
And what that is in response to is in, I would say, an awful lot of physical collectible card game, there's a concept called responses, where I play a card on my turn and my enemy out of turn can play a card in response to that, and I can play a card in response to that, and so on.

358
00:26:59,116 --> 00:27:07,340
This works great in physical collectible card games because of the nature of the interaction that you're having with the other player.

359
00:27:07,400 --> 00:27:11,902
I mean, you're basically having a conversation with the person who's sitting across from you,

360
00:27:12,202 --> 00:27:14,543
and the nature of just basic conversation has a lot of...

361
00:27:14,944 --> 00:27:20,026
shifting backwards and forwards in time and interrupting and and it's sort of built for that and so

362
00:27:20,486 --> 00:27:23,387
With a response in in a physical collectible card game

363
00:27:23,467 --> 00:27:27,749
I can go I'm gonna play a giant and now I'm gonna play a drat and they go wait wait wait wait

364
00:27:27,809 --> 00:27:29,130
No, go back to that other thing

365
00:27:29,150 --> 00:27:34,072
I'm gonna counter spell it or lightning bolt it or whatever the heck you're gonna do and it works great in that space

366
00:27:35,012 --> 00:27:35,953
in a digital space

367
00:27:36,573 --> 00:27:39,936
because you don't have that immediate back and forth, that conversation,

368
00:27:40,397 --> 00:27:44,801
it's more it's either one person's turn or the other, it causes a lot of problems.

369
00:27:45,362 --> 00:27:49,886
And so because we were designing specifically for the digital space,

370
00:27:50,407 --> 00:27:52,388
we put secrets in the game.

371
00:27:53,069 --> 00:27:55,431
And this is because we wanted to make sure we kept the depth.

372
00:27:56,132 --> 00:28:00,955
of me doing something on my turn and not knowing that I'm going to get to do all the cool stuff

373
00:28:00,975 --> 00:28:03,676
that there might be a surprise waiting for me on my opponent's side.

374
00:28:04,097 --> 00:28:09,280
And a secret is a card that you put into play that is triggered by a set of circumstances

375
00:28:09,320 --> 00:28:12,762
and when it's triggered it does a specific thing but your opponent doesn't know what

376
00:28:12,802 --> 00:28:13,922
those circumstances are.

377
00:28:14,383 --> 00:28:17,925
So they can try to play around it, but in a lot of ways it's a lot like trying to play

378
00:28:17,965 --> 00:28:18,885
around a response.

379
00:28:18,945 --> 00:28:22,488
You know, if you are seeing your opponent in Magic has two blue mana open.

380
00:28:23,229 --> 00:28:30,023
You're definitely assuming certain things and secrets are a lot the same way. So that's what we did to make it a

381
00:28:30,323 --> 00:28:32,087
digital game and emphasize that.

382
00:28:33,777 --> 00:28:39,382
Another thing we did was put digital cards in, cards that you can really only make in the digital space.

383
00:28:40,003 --> 00:28:44,847
Some of those cards we just put in because we wanted to mess around with the space and see what the possibilities were,

384
00:28:45,027 --> 00:28:50,071
like Nazdormu, which is a card that changes the turn timer to 15 seconds.

385
00:28:50,611 --> 00:28:57,617
So that's a card that wouldn't work at all in a physical space, but in a digital space it's kind of fun, it's kind of interesting,

386
00:28:57,717 --> 00:29:01,380
and as we try cards like that, we're going to find some that are super exciting.

387
00:29:03,001 --> 00:29:08,824
For me, one of the more exciting things though was where we got to solve problems by being

388
00:29:08,884 --> 00:29:11,425
in a digital space that you can't really solve in a physical space.

389
00:29:12,065 --> 00:29:17,747
So the ThoughtSteel card here was originally, long ago, a card that

390
00:29:18,668 --> 00:29:23,551
When you played it, you actually took two cards out of your opponent's deck rather than copying them.

391
00:29:24,111 --> 00:29:30,215
And when you take two cards out of your opponent's deck, there was a lot of emotional negativity to that.

392
00:29:30,615 --> 00:29:35,879
Especially from our high level players who felt like you're taking two of the cards that are my, the cards that...

393
00:29:36,479 --> 00:29:40,623
you know, cement my deck together, my endgame cards, the cards that solve problems.

394
00:29:40,904 --> 00:29:45,728
And it was very emotionally negative and we wanted to solve that problem.

395
00:29:46,129 --> 00:29:49,152
And so what we did was we thought about it and went,

