425
00:31:18,884 --> 00:31:20,945
And after talking about it a lot, we went,

426
00:31:21,005 --> 00:31:23,828
you know what, it's crazy for us to not make it a card?

427
00:31:24,488 --> 00:31:27,451
Because as a card, anyone who's ever played cards,

428
00:31:27,531 --> 00:31:29,313
whether it's, you know, a collectible card game,

429
00:31:29,473 --> 00:31:32,035
or hearts, or spades, or any card game,

430
00:31:32,535 --> 00:31:33,036
knows that...

431
00:31:33,596 --> 00:31:38,137
you can shuffle cards, that you can draw a hand of cards, that you can play cards,

432
00:31:38,157 --> 00:31:41,198
that can be discarded. There's a whole bunch of things that you understand

433
00:31:41,238 --> 00:31:45,079
about cards and a large group of people understand about cards that we don't

434
00:31:45,119 --> 00:31:49,000
have to explain and so there's no way we're giving that up because it's so

435
00:31:49,060 --> 00:31:52,221
important to have that sense of familiarity and sort of know what the

436
00:31:52,261 --> 00:31:52,901
game is going to be.

437
00:31:55,599 --> 00:32:02,744
Also, we spent a lot of time talking about the words that we used for everything because it's so important to use words people know.

438
00:32:02,764 --> 00:32:09,969
And it sort of seems obvious that the attack value of a minion should be attack, and the health value of a minion should be health.

439
00:32:10,689 --> 00:32:17,314
but one of the reasons that I point that out is because there's sometimes an idea of

440
00:32:17,394 --> 00:32:22,978
hey, our game is all about this thing, so instead of health, let's call our defensive trait morale

441
00:32:23,739 --> 00:32:28,643
and what that means is anytime a player sees morale, first off, they have to learn what the heck morale is

442
00:32:28,963 --> 00:32:32,886
and second off, they have to end up parsing your game more, because when something says

443
00:32:33,466 --> 00:32:36,969
hey, gives a minion plus three health, you don't have to parse it at all, you instantly know

444
00:32:38,202 --> 00:32:41,843
I know what that thing does, assuming I know which bubble is attack and which bubble is health.

445
00:32:42,304 --> 00:32:46,345
Whereas if it says give plus three morale, I not only have to know what morale is, I then have to

446
00:32:46,406 --> 00:32:52,408
figure it out. And so just using terms people know is super important. We spent tons of time even

447
00:32:52,468 --> 00:32:57,931
talking about what should we call the offensive trait. Okay, let's call it charge because when

448
00:32:57,951 --> 00:32:59,311
we were talking to it at Blizzard...

449
00:33:00,072 --> 00:33:05,854
Most people felt like that would be the trait that lets you attack right away. What's the defensive trait? It's taunt etc. Etc

450
00:33:05,874 --> 00:33:10,956
tons of time spent just figuring out sort of the names for things and

451
00:33:11,056 --> 00:33:12,237
even the names of

452
00:33:12,697 --> 00:33:20,660
Your spells and minions and cards was pretty important. So for instance early on we are trying to explain to the player

453
00:33:20,720 --> 00:33:26,322
What's the difference between a minion and what's the difference between a spell and it's not especially to someone who's new to collectible card games

454
00:33:26,402 --> 00:33:28,083
It's not a super obvious thing

455
00:33:29,143 --> 00:33:34,945
But if we call one of our early spells Fireball, you actually in your head already know what a Fireball does.

456
00:33:35,005 --> 00:33:37,766
You know, oh, it's going to deal some damage and go away.

457
00:33:38,266 --> 00:33:43,987
So while we're teaching you about spells, at the same time you have a thing that you know is a spell from your outside experience,

458
00:33:44,027 --> 00:33:46,928
which you can go, okay, I know how this is going to work.

459
00:33:47,648 --> 00:33:50,549
And we even actually get additional bonuses here in that...

460
00:33:52,400 --> 00:33:55,342
you probably think of Fireball as a spell from the outside experience,

461
00:33:55,602 --> 00:33:58,723
hey that's an attack spell that probably does a fair amount of damage and

462
00:33:59,183 --> 00:34:02,124
so suddenly you know, hey six damage is probably a reasonable

463
00:34:02,384 --> 00:34:05,906
reasonably fair amount of damage. So we're teaching you a bunch of stuff

464
00:34:06,126 --> 00:34:09,467
just by the names of things based on outside experience

465
00:34:09,867 --> 00:34:13,428
and that stuff is super valuable too in sort of keeping things the same for

466
00:34:13,448 --> 00:34:14,949
players and giving them what they expect.

467
00:34:17,498 --> 00:34:21,986
This is a topic that's very near and dear to my heart, supporting player stories.

468
00:34:22,667 --> 00:34:31,001
And what a player story is specifically is the thing that your buddy is going to tell you that night about their experience.

469
00:34:31,702 --> 00:34:36,744
in the game the day before and it's usually not about the narrative that they've read in the story.

470
00:34:37,184 --> 00:34:41,966
It's usually, hey I tried to play last night and the servers were down or hey I tried to play last

471
00:34:42,026 --> 00:34:47,849
night and I got crushed a couple of times or I used this crazy combo and it was awesome and those

472
00:34:47,889 --> 00:34:52,371
are the sorts of things that actual player stories are and it's important for us to embrace player

473
00:34:52,411 --> 00:34:57,733
stories and especially as a game that's trying to keep sort of our scope down and be very focused.

474
00:34:58,253 --> 00:35:03,740
We really wanted to focus on the player story and not really worry at all about the narrative story.

475
00:35:05,302 --> 00:35:10,028
So this is story time where I get to tell a story about World of Warcraft.

476
00:35:11,530 --> 00:35:14,874
This is a dungeon called Sunken Temple from World of Warcraft.

477
00:35:17,027 --> 00:35:22,991
This dungeon has a whole bunch of story to it and there's a green dragon and some trolls trying to do something or other to a god

478
00:35:23,352 --> 00:35:29,837
and despite the fact that I worked on World of Warcraft for eight years, I still couldn't actually tell you what the real story is

479
00:35:29,877 --> 00:35:31,078
but it's something like that.

480
00:35:31,838 --> 00:35:37,923
And that story was not super important to me as I was playing through World of Warcraft.

481
00:35:37,963 --> 00:35:43,007
The story that mattered to me was one where me and a bunch of friends went into Sunken Temple.

482
00:35:43,287 --> 00:35:45,649
and back in the day it was a very, very vertical dungeon.

483
00:35:45,729 --> 00:35:48,090
So we traveled all the way up to the top of the dungeon,

484
00:35:48,570 --> 00:35:50,011
and once we got to the top of the dungeon,

485
00:35:50,051 --> 00:35:51,532
we wanted to get to the bottom of the dungeon.

486
00:35:51,692 --> 00:35:53,633
And, you know, we could have fought our way back down,

487
00:35:53,673 --> 00:35:55,054
but one of my friends, she said,

488
00:35:55,074 --> 00:35:57,195
hey, there's this hole in the middle of the floor,

489
00:35:57,215 --> 00:35:58,756
why don't you just jump down?

490
00:35:58,796 --> 00:36:00,117
There's water down there, we'll jump down,

491
00:36:00,137 --> 00:36:01,397
and we'll fight, and we'll have a good time,

492
00:36:01,437 --> 00:36:03,499
and we'll avoid all that horrible walking.

493
00:36:03,579 --> 00:36:05,820
So all of us, of course, except for her, jumped,

494
00:36:06,360 --> 00:36:08,761
and we realized the water's about, you know, that deep,

495
00:36:09,542 --> 00:36:10,943
and we all died.

496
00:36:11,763 --> 00:36:13,124
and we all laughed our asses off.

497
00:36:13,784 --> 00:36:16,025
And for me, that's the story of Sunken Temple.

498
00:36:16,545 --> 00:36:19,407
And while it's not a fantastic narrative story,

499
00:36:19,987 --> 00:36:22,789
it's a story that's mine, and it's important to me.

500
00:36:23,229 --> 00:36:26,290
And so I really feel like giving players those stories

501
00:36:26,430 --> 00:36:31,253
is super important, and arguably more important than giving them, you know, the narrative story.

502
00:36:33,095 --> 00:36:39,669
So one of the things that we do in Hearthstone to support this is we create cards that create

503
00:36:39,930 --> 00:36:40,672
player stories.

504
00:36:42,467 --> 00:36:46,409
and really how we end up designing those cards is we think of a card idea and go

505
00:36:46,429 --> 00:36:50,551
I have no idea what that card idea is going to do. That's probably going to do something really

506
00:36:50,611 --> 00:36:55,393
weird and scary and when we're making these cards we actually have a general rule which is

507
00:36:56,013 --> 00:37:01,276
if the card doesn't scare us we probably should try to make it scarier and then we'll try to

508
00:37:01,336 --> 00:37:06,158
figure it out in design later or balance later if it's balanced or not.

509
00:37:07,219 --> 00:37:12,080
So this specific card, to give an example of a player story that comes from this specific card,

510
00:37:12,801 --> 00:37:17,082
this is a card that is a very powerful card for cost two, but once it comes into play,

511
00:37:17,482 --> 00:37:19,523
all of your opponent's minions are free for a turn.

512
00:37:20,143 --> 00:37:25,885
And so there's a well-known streamer who, at one point on turn one, played this card,

513
00:37:27,185 --> 00:37:29,406
using the coin, so they got an extra man on turn one.

514
00:37:29,426 --> 00:37:31,727
So on turn one they had a 4-4, which is very powerful.

515
00:37:33,687 --> 00:37:38,349
His opponent then proceeded to play a spell for free that took a bunch of cards out of his deck,

516
00:37:38,769 --> 00:37:42,629
actually the Thoughtsteal, and then another copy of that that took some more cards out of his deck,

517
00:37:43,190 --> 00:37:45,970
and then a card that took, that copied a card out of his hand,

518
00:37:46,530 --> 00:37:51,751
and then the card that he copied out of his hand he played, which, all of these were of course free,

519
00:37:51,971 --> 00:37:57,373
which summoned a random minion from the streamer's deck, which ended up being Ragnaros.

520
00:37:59,745 --> 00:38:03,106
which Ragnaros immediately fired and destroyed Milhouse Manastorm.

521
00:38:03,167 --> 00:38:07,289
So the game went horribly, horribly wrong, but it was an awesome, awesome story.

522
00:38:08,009 --> 00:38:12,471
And it's not a story that when we were creating Milhouse Manastorm we had any clue was going to happen.

523
00:38:12,551 --> 00:38:16,874
Mostly we created a card that had a lot of possibilities, a lot of open-endedness,

524
00:38:17,254 --> 00:38:21,416
and then the players gave us back the stories with all the crazy things that are happening with it.

525
00:38:23,782 --> 00:38:30,204
Another thing that is important to us is randomness, and that's certainly an area where there's a lot of, I would say, contention in the community.

526
00:38:30,804 --> 00:38:36,006
But randomness is a pretty important element for creating player stories as well.

527
00:38:36,566 --> 00:38:44,148
So this is a picture of our Arena Mode, and how Arena Mode works is you are presented with three different heroes at random.

528
00:38:44,168 --> 00:38:50,250
You pick one of those heroes, and then 30 times in a row, you choose one of the three cards that is presented to you.

529
00:38:51,105 --> 00:38:58,448
And we have some light controls on the rarity of some of these cards that show up, but we

530
00:38:58,468 --> 00:39:03,450
don't have super strong controls, and we certainly don't control the number of any specific card

531
00:39:03,470 --> 00:39:03,970
that comes up.

532
00:39:04,590 --> 00:39:09,072
So it's been known to happen in the past that you play an arena run and you get...

533
00:39:09,572 --> 00:39:15,613
you know, 11 copies of Frostbolt, or 6 Unleash the Hounds and 6 Starving Buzzards, or any

534
00:39:15,673 --> 00:39:20,794
other combination of cards, or heck, 4, or probably not 4, probably like 3 Leroy Jenkins.

535
00:39:21,974 --> 00:39:26,695
But combinations of cards that are just not possible in the real game, or I should say

536
00:39:26,715 --> 00:39:32,156
the ranked game, and that create really interesting stories.

537
00:39:32,396 --> 00:39:36,337
And one of the reasons we can actually do this is because our arena mode...

538
00:39:37,017 --> 00:39:39,659
you play until you lose three games or win 12 games.

539
00:39:39,699 --> 00:39:42,360
So no matter what the deck is, it's going to very quickly

540
00:39:43,100 --> 00:39:44,821
leave the environment one way or the other,

541
00:39:44,941 --> 00:39:46,822
and then there will be a new crazy deck that you're playing.

542
00:39:47,182 --> 00:39:49,903
And once you get to the high end, you're playing somebody else's crazy deck.

543
00:39:50,463 --> 00:39:53,605
So this randomness creates a whole lot of stories,

544
00:39:53,645 --> 00:39:55,546
and those stories, again, are really important to us

545
00:39:55,626 --> 00:39:57,026
for sort of the health of the game.

546
00:39:58,777 --> 00:40:04,563
And this is just saying that our game specifically chose to have no story and we just focus on vibes.

547
00:40:04,623 --> 00:40:08,527
So we say, hey, we're an inn, we're a warm, cozy place, come in and play games.

548
00:40:08,867 --> 00:40:11,670
And what we want to do is share your stories.

549
00:40:12,291 --> 00:40:15,154
And again, it's not because I think narrative stories are bad.

550
00:40:15,174 --> 00:40:17,316
I think in a lot of games narrative stories are great.

551
00:40:17,877 --> 00:40:19,018
I think they just require...

552
00:40:19,659 --> 00:40:23,742
a ton of work. I mean it almost has to be the primary thing you're going for if you're going

553
00:40:23,802 --> 00:40:29,947
for a narrative story and since that was not our focus we didn't go in that direction and I've

554
00:40:29,967 --> 00:40:33,610
certainly seen a lot of games that they go well we're not really going to focus on narrative

555
00:40:33,630 --> 00:40:37,794
story but we want to have one anyway and very often I see that getting in the way because

556
00:40:37,854 --> 00:40:42,577
that story is told with you know just pop-up dialogues with with text in them or something

557
00:40:42,597 --> 00:40:43,498
like that that is not

558
00:40:44,279 --> 00:40:47,499
telling a super compelling story so mostly I'm saying if you're gonna tell a

559
00:40:47,539 --> 00:40:52,081
story just focus on telling the story but in a lot of cases it's probably

560
00:40:52,121 --> 00:40:56,342
better to just stick with vibe and and let the players tell the story and

561
00:40:56,382 --> 00:41:03,884
certainly that's our belief with Hearthstone. This is also very near and

562
00:41:03,904 --> 00:41:08,305
dear to my heart and that is that emotional design matters and what I mean

563
00:41:08,345 --> 00:41:11,686
by that is it's very important to be playing paying attention to the

564
00:41:11,706 --> 00:41:13,086
emotional state of the player.

565
00:41:14,182 --> 00:41:16,864
as they're playing the game and as they're encountering things in the game

566
00:41:16,905 --> 00:41:23,771
and in a lot of cases that's more important than sort of the mechanical design

567
00:41:23,912 --> 00:41:25,814
or in some cases even high level balance.

568
00:41:28,383 --> 00:41:37,775
One thing that we've discovered is very often there's emotion in unintended places that as a game developer certainly we don't necessarily, or I often don't think about and should think about more.

569
00:41:38,776 --> 00:41:46,565
And so for instance, a moment of high emotion that's going to probably be higher emotion than anything else a player will encounter in your game is when they...

570
00:41:47,772 --> 00:41:53,037
run into the server being down, or there being an error message, or a number of things like

571
00:41:53,137 --> 00:41:57,942
that, that are not things that normally we design for, but I like, I think it's pretty

572
00:41:57,982 --> 00:42:00,885
important to pay attention to, sort of the emotional state.

573
00:42:01,345 --> 00:42:05,849
And this is actually an example of where we changed the game a little bit to make the

574
00:42:05,890 --> 00:42:07,071
emotion of the game better.

575
00:42:07,832 --> 00:42:12,900
So this is our spinner and this comes up whenever you're doing matchmaking and

576
00:42:12,920 --> 00:42:17,108
It has a bunch of funny things that it says and it always ends up on well back in the day

577
00:42:17,148 --> 00:42:20,594
it always ended up on a perfect opponent and

578
00:42:22,428 --> 00:42:26,070
When you actually play the game after you're matched with with this opponent

579
00:42:26,550 --> 00:42:31,713
Sometimes it is a blowout whether it's because they got good cards or you got bad cards or they're a better player than you

580
00:42:31,753 --> 00:42:35,795
There's all kinds of reasons why it could be a blowout even if it was a pretty good match

581
00:42:36,255 --> 00:42:40,297
But what that means is early on a player would see a perfect opponent

582
00:42:40,997 --> 00:42:43,099
get blown out in the match and go,

583
00:42:43,119 --> 00:42:45,061
I'm super pissed at Blizzard.

584
00:42:45,462 --> 00:42:47,924
This makes me angry because it said a perfect opponent

585
00:42:47,964 --> 00:42:49,966
and this did not feel like a perfect opponent.

586
00:42:50,406 --> 00:42:52,728
And so we actually just changed the text

587
00:42:52,768 --> 00:42:56,932
to read a worthy opponent because it changed qualitatively

588
00:42:56,972 --> 00:42:59,054
sort of the emotional response.

589
00:42:59,314 --> 00:43:01,056
I mean, it's still never fun to get blown out,

590
00:43:01,497 --> 00:43:04,339
but it was qualitatively better just changing the wording

591
00:43:04,379 --> 00:43:06,701
and setting the expectation slightly differently.

592
00:43:08,872 --> 00:43:14,534
We also do a lot of design for Emotion. This is a discard from the physical WoW trading card game.

593
00:43:15,334 --> 00:43:19,436
Discard card and this is a mechanic that we actually don't do any of in Hearthstone.

594
00:43:20,116 --> 00:43:28,400
Because the effect of playing discard and certain other types of mechanics on your opponent is super disheartening.

595
00:43:28,760 --> 00:43:31,041
It sort of makes your opponent feel powerless.

596
00:43:31,621 --> 00:43:36,425
and it's sort of a weird state actually because it's fun to play discard decks and

597
00:43:36,865 --> 00:43:43,109
Counterspell decks is another type of deck that we're not really supporting or resource destruction all of those things. It's fun to play those

598
00:43:43,950 --> 00:43:49,374
But it's not fun to have those played against you and we felt like the emotional negativity that came

599
00:43:49,894 --> 00:43:55,838
From having that played against you was so strong that we didn't feel like that we could really include those mechanics in our game

600
00:43:56,854 --> 00:44:09,618
And it's actually in some cases a problem for us because there are certain types of decks in the metagame that it would be useful if we had discard as a tool to put in players hands to deal with sort of those types of decks.

601
00:44:10,059 --> 00:44:13,240
But the emotional negativity is so strong so we're just not going to do it.

602
00:44:14,100 --> 00:44:16,581
We're designing for emotion and just taking those straight out.

603
00:44:17,941 --> 00:44:20,122
We also do a lot of balance for emotion.

604
00:44:20,142 --> 00:44:24,763
A significant number of our changes over the last six months or so have been made.

605
00:44:25,926 --> 00:44:30,989
actually for emotional responses and emotional feedback rather than like high level balance

606
00:44:31,629 --> 00:44:36,432
thoughts and mind control is one of those cards that we changed. It's a card that when you play

607
00:44:36,472 --> 00:44:40,875
it you take an opponent's minion and put it onto your side and now you own it and the emotional

608
00:44:40,935 --> 00:44:44,677
response to that is is very strongly negative and

609
00:44:45,734 --> 00:44:47,396
we heard all these people complaining everywhere,

610
00:44:47,636 --> 00:44:50,358
oh my god, mind control is too powerful, I can't play against it,

611
00:44:50,398 --> 00:44:53,601
it's the strongest card in the game, and we looked at the numbers,

612
00:44:54,182 --> 00:44:58,766
and it was just fine, the card was not an overpowered card.

613
00:44:58,786 --> 00:45:02,249
The problem with the card is it felt super bad to have it played against you,

614
00:45:02,309 --> 00:45:05,132
so we actually increased the cost of the card significantly

615
00:45:06,053 --> 00:45:08,695
to make it so that it would be seen less.

616
00:45:09,196 --> 00:45:14,261
sort of in the game as a whole, that it's more of a niche card, even though from a pure balance point of view,

617
00:45:14,301 --> 00:45:20,147
we didn't have to make any changes to it. It was just an emotionally balanced card or an emotionally unbalanced card,

618
00:45:20,167 --> 00:45:21,729
I guess, that we felt like we needed to change.

619
00:45:24,165 --> 00:45:28,967
Also, one thing that was pretty interesting that we talked a lot about when we were designing the game is

620
00:45:29,468 --> 00:45:35,311
when do we provide the audio and visual feedback to support specific emotions.

621
00:45:35,711 --> 00:45:42,174
So, when we were first building the game, our artists were working on the effects of attacking

622
00:45:42,194 --> 00:45:46,737
and they're like, we're gonna make this awesome effect when my minion crashes into the enemy hero or your minion,

623
00:45:47,077 --> 00:45:48,198
it's gonna be super cool.

624
00:45:49,038 --> 00:46:04,177
And after we talked about it for a while, we realized that while the attack is a very important moment narratively, like in a movie, whatever, that is going to be the high moment of emotional impact in Hearthstone.

625
00:46:04,938 --> 00:46:09,421
By the time something's attacking, you probably actually know what it's going to be attacking.

626
00:46:10,281 --> 00:46:13,643
Or if you don't, you're like, eh, he could attack this or this. Yeah, he attacked that.

627
00:46:13,683 --> 00:46:15,424
It's not emotionally high moment.

628
00:46:15,804 --> 00:46:21,087
So instead, what we did is we, instead of focusing our audio and visual effects there as much,

629
00:46:21,147 --> 00:46:22,568
we focused a lot more on...

630
00:46:23,549 --> 00:46:26,990
summoning cards into play because actually the high emotional moment in a

631
00:46:27,010 --> 00:46:30,932
game of Hearthstone is when my opponent first put something into play because it

632
00:46:30,952 --> 00:46:34,734
could be anything it could change the game entirely and you just have no idea

